There's a roster of football clubs, based on the leagues they play in. Total number of such clubs are usually between 40 - 50.
Each team, which should be around 2-3 members, will be allotted a club, based on preferences they fill in. That'll be done by us and should be finalized before a day of the event, if possible.
Each club will have a certain budget and set of objectives, both based upon the position of the club financially and performance wise. These objectives are mostly based on strengthening the squad or clearing players not required, etc. Take cues from last year's objectives.
For the participating teams, you'll be handing them team rosters, i.e. the list of players in the squads of each club and their transfer values and other details like playing position and age; and the objectives list of the particular club, which was allotted to that team only.
Now their aim is to fulfill the objectives and keep the budget in positive, and try to strengthen the squad to their wish after they are done with the objectives. All of this is done via negotiations among the teams, during a period called transfer window. There should be at least 3 such windows, with time varying according the time duration of the event with break in between each window for the organizers to proof check the deals done and register it. During such breaks, the teams aren't supposed to negotiate at all.
These transfers are validated via what we call transfer slips, where the name of the player to be transferred, clubs between whom the transfer is happening and signature of one of the organizers, who are known as moderators. Then, during the breaks, the moderators, especially the chief moderators checks if the minimum transfer value of the player has been met or not. Transfer shouldn't happen between clubs if the price involved falls short of the transfer value of the player. There are also swap deals, where a player from each club goes the either way, and it may involve cash deals, so it has to be dealt with carefully.
Then there is something called transfer shortlist, where the clubs i.e. the participating teams can put their players up for sale. That is something which is to be displayed via the projector for everyone to see and attract potential buyers.
Now coming to the judging criteria, teams will be first judged upon the fact whether they have completed their objectives or not, irrespective of whether they were not able to due to some random reason, if yes, then it comes the budget left, this is something which is relative, since there is no fixed budget, after that it comes to the squad depth and strength, basically how good is the team they created.
